      <p>All SDS patients were recruited from the LC Campbell Cognitive Neurology Research Unit, Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre at the University of Toronto (age: 71‚Äâ¬±‚Äâ10, 28 Males). The T1‚Äêweighted three‚Äêdimensional volumetric scan was acquired using a 1.5 Tesla Signa system (GE Healthcare, Chicago, Illinois). The acquisition parameters for the T1 spoiled gradient echo sequence were: 124 slices; matrix, 256‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ192; 22‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ16.5 cm FOV; number of excitations, 1; echo time/repetition time, 35‚Äâms/5 ms; flip angle, 35¬∞, and in‚Äêplane resolution of 0.859‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ0.859‚Äâmm with slice thickness between 1.2 and 1.4 mm depending on head size. ADNI subjects were scanned at multiple sites using a mixture of 1.5 T (<italic>N</italic> = 68) and 3 T (<italic>N</italic> = 67) scanners (age: 75‚Äâ¬±‚Äâ8, 70 males). Participants were nearly equal in cohort size for the three diagnostic groups (normal, MCI and AD), and three scanner major manufacturers (GE, Siemens, and Philips). The ADNI‚ÄêGO/2 MRI protocol has been optimized to provide comparable images from different 3 T platforms from the three manufacturers. The T1 weighted magnetization prepared rapid gradient echo (MPRAGE) had the following parameters: TR/TE/TI = 2300/2.95/900‚Äâms, sagittal, 1.1‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ1.1‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ1.2 mm spatial resolution. UPenn subjects were scanned at a 3 T Siemens Trio scanner using an eight‚Äêchannel head coil and body coil transmitter. The T1‚Äêweighted structural MRI scan used the MPRAGE sequence with the following parameters: TR = 1,620‚Äâms, TE = 3.87‚Äâms, TI = 950‚Äâms, flip angle = 15¬∞, and voxel size 0.9375‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ0.9375‚Äâ√ó‚Äâ1 mm.</p>
